{
  "text": "The creation of an erythrocyte, a highly specialized cell, requires the upregulation of dedicated proteins, like hemoglobin, and the elimination of all detrimental or simply unnecessary proteins and structures ( Fig. 1 ). Both types of processes are required. As the changes are dramatic and easily studied, the reticulocyte provides Normal and disordered reticulocyte maturation Ney 155 an excellent model for the study of cellular remodeling. As discussed here, cellular remodeling in the reticulocyte itself appears to occur through two central processes: vesicular trafficking and autophagy. Although they are considered distinct processes, they may overlap at the cellular and molecular levels. At the cellular level, both terminate with exocytosis, suggesting a common mechanism. Further, autophagosomes can fuse with MVEs, leading to hybrid organelles [CITATION_1] . At the molecular level, there is recent evidence of shared components between the vesicular trafficking and autophagy pathways [80 ,81 ] . In this regard, in higher eukaryotes, inactivation of the ubiqutin-like conjugation pathways leads to only a partial loss of autophagy activity [64 ,80 ] . Whether a component of the vesicular trafficking machinery supplies this redundant activity remains to be determined.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "23144533"
